<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=2 -->
Section 23.697&blank;Wing Flap Controls
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
Proposed new &sect;23.697(c) would provide safety standards for the wing flap control lever designs installed in
airplanes that use wing flap settings other than fully retracted when showing compliance with &sect;23.145. This
revision is needed to ensure that the flap settings, which establish the safe operation of the airplane, can be positively
selected.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=2 -->
Section 23.701&blank;Flap Interconnection
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
Section 23.701 (a)(1) and (a)(2) would be revised to clarify the requirements for flap systems installed on part 23
airplanes. Following the revision of &sect;23.701, as adopted by Amendment No. 23&hyph;42 (56 FR 353, January 3,
1991), the FAA discovered that the new requirements could be interpreted in a way that was not intended and that this
interpretation could result in approval of airplanes with unsafe flight characteristics in the event of flap failure.
To clarify the intent of the requirements, the FAA issued on March 14, 1991, a policy letter to all aircraft certification
offices that provided guidance for the correct application of the requirements.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Since then, the FAA has reexamined the requirements and determined that &sect;23.701 (a)(1) and (a)(2) need to be
revised to ensure that a failure of the flap system would not create an asymmetric flap configuration that could result
in an unsafe flight condition. Therefore, &sect;23.701 (a)(1) and (a)(2) would be revised to clarify that one of the
following would apply:
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) The moveable flap surfaces must be synchronized by a mechanical interconnection or by an approved equivalent
means, that is independent of the flap drive system.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The wing flap system must be designed so that any failures of the flap system that would result in an unsafe flight
characteristic of the airplane, such as flap asymmetry, is extremely improbable.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
These revisions would ensure that a failure of the flap drive systems will not result in a flap asymmetry configuration.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=2 -->
Section 23.703&blank;Takeoff Warning System
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
This proposed new section would require a takeoff warning system on some commuter category airplanes. The requirement
would be applicable if the flight evaluation showed that an unsafe takeoff condition would result if lift devices
or longitudinal trim devices are set to any position outside the approved takeoff range. If the evaluation shows that
no unsafe condition would result at any setting of these devices, a takeoff warning system would not be required. For
those airplanes on which a warning system must be installed, the proposal would provide requirements for the installation
of the system.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=2 -->
Section 23.723&blank;Shock Absorption Tests
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
Paragraph (b) of this section would be revised by changing the word ``reserved'' in the phrase ``reserved energy absorption
capacity'' to ``reserve.''
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=2 -->
Section 23.729&blank;Landing Gear Extension and Retraction System
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
This proposal would revise &sect;23.729(e) to clarify that a landing gear indicator is required for each gear. The
last sentence of current &sect;23.729(e) would also be removed. This sentence, which states that the switches may
be located where they are operated by the actual landing gear locking latch or device, is advisory material and should
not be included in the requirements. If future guidance is needed to identify acceptable switch locations, Advisory
Circular 23.701&hyph;1 will be revised to include that information.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
This proposal would also add a new &sect;23.729(g) requiring that if the landing gear bay is used as the location for
equipment other than landing gear, the equipment must be designed and installed to minimize damage. On larger airplanes,
such as the commuter category, a primary cause of damage to such equipment would be tire burst. In addition, service
history has shown that rocks, water, and slush enter the landing gear bay and cause damage. The equipment on any size
airplane should be protected from damage by such external sources.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
